description:

From Takahiro Miyashita‚Äôs last Number (N)ine Collection entitled ‚ÄúA Closed Feeing‚Äù regarded by many as his best work ever.
Number (N)ine is very well known for its grunge cardigans - this is one of the better ones imo, it‚Äôs got a mohair style look to it so its very shaggy and fuzzy, pockets which is a rare sight on nine cardigans, and a nice drapey fit. Perfect grunge look.
Stop buying reprints and fake number (n)ine - this is authentic from takahiro era, its sad seeing reprint mohairs sell for 500 plus when authentic ones designed by Takahiro are being sold this low. Flex on them mfers who are copping reprint Kooks co. and buy this.
Mohair cardigans from nine are going for insane prices upwards to 5-1000 - ive listed this one at a reasonable price in hopes someone who is knowledgeable and appreciative will snag it since I no longer fit.
Size 2 fits a true medium in my opinion, but also can fit a small for a more loose fit, or if you like a tight fit you could be on the bigger size of a medium.
Some pilling and tiny holes which is to be expected for a piece over 13 years old - adds to the grunge aesthetic obviously

Takahiro Miyashita is known for his youth-culture-centered, punk-ish artistic vision, or, as he explains it, ‚ÄúAll my work is about rebellion and not being conventional‚Äù (The New York Times, 2008). This attitude lines up perfectly with ‚ÄúNightcrawler‚Äù, which is Number (N)ine Spring-Summer 2005 collection debuted in the French capital of Paris. This collection takes big inspiration from punk culture, with a diverse range of classic punk style characteristics being featured throughout the runway, including- asymmetrical silhouettes, spiked bracelets, deconstructed garments and black leather vests. Though not just ‚Äògeneric‚Äô punk-ish leather garments, but rather, an actual challenge of norms with a strong sense of androgyny throughout the collection.
These above-listed items are probably collection‚Äôs most iconic pieces, with their unique, asymmetrical sleeveless shape being used on multiple garments and worn on multiple looks.
My listing is for a set of both the hoodie and the tee. They‚Äôre both in excellent condition with no defects whatsoever. All of their tears, rips and holes are intentional as you may see on the runway video. They‚Äôre tagged as Japanese size 2 and they fit like US small or tight medium. If you‚Äôre looking to recreate that triangle shape from the runway you‚Äôd have to wear the tee reversed as both items are left-sleeved, however, I wore it that way a few times without any issues of comfort so it should be just fine. It is also not noticeable to be worn reserved once you wear the hoodie above the tee (refer to the third picture for example).

One of the most incredible pieces designed by The Soloist during his years at Number (N)ine; released as part of his AW05 collection ‚ÄúThe High Streets‚Äù.
Wearing this will make you feel like a dark lord of the streets. Replete with details, and thoughtful luxurious touches, such as the smooth, and soft padded inner lining, the extremely supple and soft wool portion, the double layered heavy-weight cotton used for the sleeves- the insane material quality can be instantly felt as soon as you don this. It‚Äôs clothing that harkens back to a time before major fashion conglomerates and even largely independent anti-fashion brands began cost-cutting measures to increase their margins at the cost of the material quality of their creations.
Open to hearing offers, as I would love to see what I perceive to be a work of art in its own right being worn by someone who can appreciate it more than I can.
Condition: 9/10- old, but kept in outstanding condition. Please note that the white seam line between the leather and wool is not a defect, and that the cotton sleeves are naturally distressed, and not tear from wear.

Takahiro Miyashita's Number (N)ine Spring/Summer 2004 collection entitled "Dream Baby Dream" was inspired by the counterculture of ‚ÄúMods & Rockabilly‚Äù of the late 1960s and the New York punk scene of the early 1970s with influences from artists such as: Patti Smith, Debbie Harry (Blondie), Richard Hell (The Voidoids) and Alan Vega (Suicide). Also, incorporating notable references from the British punk band members (like Paul Simonon) from ‚ÄúThe Clash‚Äù among others. This collection highlighted the brand‚Äôs last runway show held locally in Japan and took place in a parking garage with notable attendees including Nobuhiko Kitamura from ‚ÄúHysteric Glamour‚Äù. The clothing was a mix of streetwear and tailoring with great diversity of garments and accessories, including, but not limited to: bombers, blousons, blazers, vests, hoodies, jeans, trousers, skull-shaped rings, mesh knits and much more‚Ä¶ Color palette was derived from shades of black with some offerings done in bold ‚Äúhi-vis‚Äù neon primary colors and even exotic animal prints like tiger and leopard fur patterns. Apart from the expected distressing of the clothing, the maximalist use of zipper detailing and some ‚Äúbondage‚Äù like straps were also included on some pieces. This was the collection that showcased the ‚ÄúDouble Skull'' motifs that blew up in popularity within the ‚Äúarchive fashion‚Äù scene in the likes of the ‚ÄúJedi‚Äù hoodies, graphic ‚ÄúDead Rockers‚Äù tees and velour track jackets infamously worn by Ian Connor and Travis Scott.

sub_title: Number Nine ‚ÄúTouch Me I‚Äôm Sick‚Äù Velour Cardigan

description:
Takahiro Miyashita‚Äôs Fall 2009 capsule collection retains an untouched legacy. Doubling as both his final showing and long awaited partnership with photographer Charles Peterson, the product summarized Miyashita‚Äôs reign at his eponymous label. Throughout the 90‚Äôs, Peterson established a relationship with Sub-pop, documenting the rise of Nirvana, Pearl Jam and others. Almost exclusively captured in a monochromatic format, the creative refused to crop or alter his imagery to preserve an authentic attitude. His photos were raw and personal, seen through his eyes at the forefront of pop-culture‚Äôs upheaval.
Captured in the pit of Endfest, a music festival hosted in Washington D.C, Charles Peterson illustrates the raw and unapologetic attitude local youth retained. Shot at Mudhoney‚Äôs 1991 set, the belligerent crowd is seen in the heat of an angst filled cesspool, flaring with obscenities and fists. Congruent with the capsule collection, this graphic is printed atop a black crewneck, complemented with lettering that reads ‚ÄúPhoto by Charles Peterson‚Äù. In great condition throughout, fitting a size medium.
